✅ What’s actually happening
    You installed sharp on your local machine (Windows/Mac), but AWS Lambda runs on Amazon Linux (linux-x64).

So:
    Your node_modules contains wrong native binaries
    Lambda expects: sharp-linux-x64.node
    But your build has: sharp-win32 or sharp-darwin

🔥 Correct Fix (Production-safe)
    ✅ Option 1: Install sharp for Lambda (recommended)

    Run this inside a Linux environment:
    rm -rf node_modules package-lock.json

    npm install --platform=linux --arch=x64 sharp

✅ Option 2: Use Docker (BEST practice)
    Since you're already using Lambda + Docker, do this:

    Dockerfile (correct version)
    FROM public.ecr.aws/lambda/nodejs:18

    WORKDIR ${LAMBDA_TASK_ROOT}

    COPY package*.json ./

    RUN npm install --omit=dev

    COPY . .

    CMD ["handler.handler"]

👉 Then build inside Docker:

    docker build -t lambda-sharp .

    This ensures:

    sharp is compiled for Amazon Linux
    No binary mismatch

✅ Option 3: Use Lambda Layer (cleanest for reuse)

    Instead of bundling sharp in your app:
    mkdir sharp-layer
    cd sharp-layer

    npm init -y
    npm install sharp --platform=linux --arch=x64

    Zip it:

    zip -r sharp-layer.zip node_modules

    Attach this layer to Lambda.

    ⚠️ Important Gotchas
    1. Node version mismatch

        Ensure:
            Lambda runtime = Node 18
            Your build environment = Node 18

    2. --ignore-scripts issue
    If you ever ran:
        npm install --ignore-scripts

        👉 sharp will break because it needs postinstall scripts.

        Fix:
        npm install --ignore-scripts=false

    3. Serverless Framework fix

    If using Serverless:

package:
  excludeDevDependencies: true

And add:

custom:
  webpack:
    includeModules: true
